{"title_page": "Madison Prewett", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|American television personality}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Madison Prewett \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Madison Rose Prewett\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1996|03|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Alabama]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Auburn University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| occupation         = Television personality\n| home_town          = [[Auburn, Alabama]], U.S.\n}}\n'''Madison Rose Prewett'''<ref>{{cite tweet|author=Chad Prewett|user=coach_prewettAU|number=1237569475999719424|date=March 10, 2020|title=Proud is an understatement. I believe in you and support you always Madi Rose!|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> (born March 25, 1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-Lbdzin5e-/|author=Madison Prewett|date=March 25, 2020|title=23 you were a good one, here\u2019s to 24!|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> is a American television personality. She received national recognition after appearing as a contestant on [[The Bachelor (season 24)|season 24]] of [[The Bachelor (American TV series)|''The Bachelor'']], starring [[Peter Weber (television personality)|Peter Weber]]. She finished as runner-up after voluntarily leaving the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/bachelor-finale-peter-weber-devastated-madison-prewett-leaves-show/|title=Bachelor Finale: Madison Prewett Dumps Peter Weber as His Mom Begs Him to Pick Hannah Ann Sluss|last=Corinthios|first=Aurelie|date=March 9, 2020|publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPrewett was raised in [[Auburn, Alabama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wtvm.com/2019/12/17/daughter-auburn-basketballs-director-operations-compete-bachelor/|title=Daughter of Auburn Basketball\u2019s Director of Operations to compete on \u2018The Bachelor\u2019|date=December 17, 2019|work=[[WTVM]]}}</ref><ref name=\"price\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/madison-prewett-from-the-bachelor-once-won-8000-on-the-price-is-right-19742181|title=Madison Prewett From 'The Bachelor' Once Won $8,000 On 'The Price Is Right'|website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref> She played basketball for Lee-Scott Academy in high school and has won four state championships.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.marieclaire.com/culture/a29811901/who-is-madison-prewett-the-bachelor/|title=Why 'Bachelor' Contestant Madison Prewett Is Important|last=Igoe|first=Katherine J.|date=January 30, 2020|magazine=[[Marie Claire]]|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maxpreps.com/news/gHvDL2tPl0SVBiI02ue-9Q/watch--the-bachelor-contender-madison-prewett-was-a-high-school-basketball-star.htm|title=Watch: 'The Bachelor' contender Madison Prewett was a high school basketball star|date=February 20, 2020|work=[[MaxPreps]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> She competed in the 2014 [[Miss Alabama Teen USA]] pageant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missalabamausa.com/contestants-teen/auburn-2/|title=Madison Prewett \u2022 Auburn|publisher=Miss Alabama USA/Teen USA Pageants|language=en-US|access-date=February 4, 2020|archivedate=March 11, 2020|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200311194409/https://www.missalabamausa.com/contestants-teen/auburn-2/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/06/who-is-madison-prewett-meet-the-bachelor-contestant-vying-for-peter-weber/|title=Who is Madison Prewett? Meet \u2018The Bachelor\u2019 contestant vying for Peter Weber|last=DeNinno|first=Nadine|date=January 6, 2020|website=[[New York Post]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Prewett graduated from [[Auburn University]], where her father, Chad Prewett, serves as Director of Operations for the men's basketball team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theplainsman.com/article/2019/09/bachelor-contestant-has-auburn-ties|title='Bachelor' contestant has Auburn ties|date=September 18, 2019|work=[[The Auburn Plainsman]]|last=Hurley|first=Elizabeth|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/life/2020/02/madison-prewetts-future-on-the-bachelor-in-doubt-after-peter-admits-intimacy-with-other-women.html|title=How did Madison Prewett's ultimatum go on The Bachelor?|date=February 25, 2020|publisher=AL.com|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> While at Auburn, she was a member of [[Pi Beta Phi]] sorority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/montgomery/2014/08/see_full_listing_of_auburn_uni.html|title=See full listing of Auburn University sorority pledges following Bid Day 2014|last=Sutton|first=Amber|date=August 16, 2014|publisher=AL.com|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to appearing on ''The Bachelor'', Prewett worked as a foster parent recruiter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/everything-know-bachelor-contestant-madison-191606853.html|title=Everything to Know About The Bachelor Contestant Madison Prewett, Who Got the First 1-on-1 Date|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|date=January 8, 2020|last=Todisco|first=Eric|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reality television ==\nIn April 2019, she appeared on the [[CBS]] show, [[The Price Is Right (American game show)|''The Price Is Right'']], where she won $8,000.<ref name=\"price\" />\n\nIn January 2020, Prewett was a contestant on the [[The Bachelor (season 24)|season 24th]] season of [[The Bachelor (American TV series)|''The Bachelor'']], where she finished as runner-up after voluntarily leaving the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc.go.com/shows/the-bachelor/cast/season-24-madison-2020|title=Madison|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]|language=en|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/sports/college/auburn/2020/01/07/madison-prewett-the-bachelor-brings-buzz-auburn-mens-basketball-chad-prewett-bruce-pearl-abc/2834394001/|title=Auburn coach Bruce Pearl 'glued' to The Bachelor with Madison Prewett as a contestant|last=Vitale|first=Josh|date=January 7, 2020|publisher=[[Montgomery Advertiser]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> During The Bachelor's live ''After the Final Rose'' special, Weber and Prewett admitted to still having feelings for each other and stated they would take things one day at a time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/au/news/1129962/where-peter-weber-and-madison-prewett-stand-after-the-bachelor-finale|title=Where Peter Weber and Madison Prewett Stand After The Bachelor Finale|last=Aiello|first=McKenna|date=March 10, 2020|website=[[E! News]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> However, on March 12, 2020, they revealed that they had decided not to pursue a relationship with one another.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/bachelor-peter-weber-and-madison-prewett-were-never-really-back-together-and-hes-still-single/|title=Bachelor Peter Weber and Madison Prewett Were Never Really \u2018Back Together\u2019 \u2014 and He\u2019s Still Single|last=Corriston|first=Michele|date=March 18, 2020|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prewett, Madison}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:Bachelor Nation contestants]]\n[[Category:Auburn University alumni]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|American television personality}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Madison Prewett \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Madison Rose Prewett\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1996|03|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Alabama]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Auburn University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| occupation         = Television personality\n| home_town          = [[Auburn, Alabama]], U.S.\n}}\n'''Madison Rose Prewett'''<ref>{{cite tweet|author=Chad Prewett|user=coach_prewettAU|number=1237569475999719424|date=March 10, 2020|title=Proud is an understatement. I believe in you and support you always Madi Rose!|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> (born March 25, 1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-Lbdzin5e-/|author=Madison Prewett|date=March 25, 2020|title=23 you were a good one, here\u2019s to 24!|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> is a American television personality. She received national recognition after appearing as a contestant on [[The Bachelor (season 24)|season 24]] of [[The Bachelor (American TV series)|''The Bachelor'']], starring [[Peter Weber (television personality)|Peter Weber]]. She finished as runner-up after voluntarily leaving the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/bachelor-finale-peter-weber-devastated-madison-prewett-leaves-show/|title=Bachelor Finale: Madison Prewett Dumps Peter Weber as His Mom Begs Him to Pick Hannah Ann Sluss|last=Corinthios|first=Aurelie|date=March 9, 2020|publisher=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPrewett was raised in [[Auburn, Alabama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wtvm.com/2019/12/17/daughter-auburn-basketballs-director-operations-compete-bachelor/|title=Daughter of Auburn Basketball\u2019s Director of Operations to compete on \u2018The Bachelor\u2019|date=December 17, 2019|work=[[WTVM]]}}</ref><ref name=\"price\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/madison-prewett-from-the-bachelor-once-won-8000-on-the-price-is-right-19742181|title=Madison Prewett From 'The Bachelor' Once Won $8,000 On 'The Price Is Right'|website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref> She played basketball for Lee-Scott Academy in high school and has won four state championships.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.marieclaire.com/culture/a29811901/who-is-madison-prewett-the-bachelor/|title=Why 'Bachelor' Contestant Madison Prewett Is Important|last=Igoe|first=Katherine J.|date=January 30, 2020|magazine=[[Marie Claire]]|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maxpreps.com/news/gHvDL2tPl0SVBiI02ue-9Q/watch--the-bachelor-contender-madison-prewett-was-a-high-school-basketball-star.htm|title=Watch: 'The Bachelor' contender Madison Prewett was a high school basketball star|date=February 20, 2020|work=[[MaxPreps]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> She competed in the 2014 [[Miss Alabama Teen USA]] pageant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missalabamausa.com/contestants-teen/auburn-2/|title=Madison Prewett \u2022 Auburn|publisher=Miss Alabama USA/Teen USA Pageants|language=en-US|access-date=February 4, 2020|archivedate=March 11, 2020|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200311194409/https://www.missalabamausa.com/contestants-teen/auburn-2/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/06/who-is-madison-prewett-meet-the-bachelor-contestant-vying-for-peter-weber/|title=Who is Madison Prewett? Meet \u2018The Bachelor\u2019 contestant vying for Peter Weber|last=DeNinno|first=Nadine|date=January 6, 2020|website=[[New York Post]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Prewett graduated from [[Auburn University]], where her father, Chad Prewett, serves as Director of Operations for the men's basketball team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theplainsman.com/article/2019/09/bachelor-contestant-has-auburn-ties|title='Bachelor' contestant has Auburn ties|date=September 18, 2019|work=[[The Auburn Plainsman]]|last=Hurley|first=Elizabeth|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/life/2020/02/madison-prewetts-future-on-the-bachelor-in-doubt-after-peter-admits-intimacy-with-other-women.html|title=How did Madison Prewett's ultimatum go on The Bachelor?|date=February 25, 2020|publisher=AL.com|language=en|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> While at Auburn, she was a member of Pi Beta Phi sorority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/montgomery/2014/08/see_full_listing_of_auburn_uni.html|title=See full listing of Auburn University sorority pledges following Bid Day 2014|last=Sutton|first=Amber|date=August 16, 2014|publisher=AL.com|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to appearing on ''The Bachelor'', Prewett worked as a foster parent recruiter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/everything-know-bachelor-contestant-madison-191606853.html|title=Everything to Know About The Bachelor Contestant Madison Prewett, Who Got the First 1-on-1 Date|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|date=January 8, 2020|last=Todisco|first=Eric|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reality television ==\nIn April 2019, she appeared on the [[CBS]] show, [[The Price Is Right (American game show)|''The Price Is Right'']], where she won $8,000.<ref name=\"price\" />\n\nIn January 2020, Prewett was a contestant on the [[The Bachelor (season 24)|season 24th]] season of [[The Bachelor (American TV series)|''The Bachelor'']], where she finished as runner-up after voluntarily leaving the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc.go.com/shows/the-bachelor/cast/season-24-madison-2020|title=Madison|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]|language=en|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/sports/college/auburn/2020/01/07/madison-prewett-the-bachelor-brings-buzz-auburn-mens-basketball-chad-prewett-bruce-pearl-abc/2834394001/|title=Auburn coach Bruce Pearl 'glued' to The Bachelor with Madison Prewett as a contestant|last=Vitale|first=Josh|date=January 7, 2020|publisher=[[Montgomery Advertiser]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> During The Bachelor's live ''After the Final Rose'' special, Weber and Prewett admitted to still having feelings for each other and stated they would take things one day at a time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/au/news/1129962/where-peter-weber-and-madison-prewett-stand-after-the-bachelor-finale|title=Where Peter Weber and Madison Prewett Stand After The Bachelor Finale|last=Aiello|first=McKenna|date=March 10, 2020|website=[[E! News]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> However, on March 12, 2020, they revealed that they had decided not to pursue a relationship with one another.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/bachelor-peter-weber-and-madison-prewett-were-never-really-back-together-and-hes-still-single/|title=Bachelor Peter Weber and Madison Prewett Were Never Really \u2018Back Together\u2019 \u2014 and He\u2019s Still Single|last=Corriston|first=Michele|date=March 18, 2020|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prewett, Madison}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:Bachelor Nation contestants]]\n[[Category:Auburn University alumni]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n", "name_user": "Naraht", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkPi Beta PhiusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madison_Prewett"}
{"title_page": "The Little Rascals (film)", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{short description|1994 family comedy by Penelope Spheeris}}\n{{more citations needed|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Little Rascals\n| image          = Little rascals ver2.jpg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Penelope Spheeris]]\n| producer       = Bill Oakes<br />[[Michael King]]<br />[[Gerald R. Molen]]\n| writer         = Paul Guay<br />Stephen Mazur<br />Penelope Spheeris\n| story          = Paul Guay<br />Stephen Mazur<br />Penelope Spheeris<br />[[Mike Scott (musician)|Mike Scott]]<br />Robert Wolterstorff\n| based on       = {{basedon|''[[Our Gang]]''|[[Hal Roach]]}}\n| starring = {{Plain list |\n* [[Travis Tedford]]\n* Kevin Jamal Woods\n* Jordan Warkol\n* Zachary Mabry\n* [[Ross Bagley|Ross Elliot Bagley]]\n* [[Courtland Mead]]\n* Sam Saletta\n* Blake Jeremy Collins\n* [[Blake McIver Ewing]]\n* Juliette Brewer\n* Heather Karasek\n* Brittany Ashton Holmes\n* [[Bug Hall]]\n* Elmer\n* [[Pete the Pup|Petey]]}}\n| music          = [[William Ross (composer)|William Ross]]\n| cinematography = Richard Bowen (operator)\n| editing        = Ross Albert<br />[[Peter Teschner]]\n| studio         = [[Amblin Entertainment]]<br />[[KingWorld|KingWorld Filmed Entertainment]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1994|08|05}}\n| runtime        = 82 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          = $67.3 million\n| image_size     = 215px\n}}\n'''''The Little Rascals''''' is a 1994 American family comedy film produced by [[Amblin Entertainment]], and released by [[Universal Pictures]] on August 5, 1994. The film is an adaptation of [[Hal Roach]]'s ''[[Our Gang]]'', a series of [[short film]]s of the 1920s, 1930s, and 1940s (many of which were broadcast on television as ''The Little Rascals'') which centered on the adventures of a group of neighborhood [[children]]. The film, with a screenplay by Paul Guay, Stephen Mazur, and [[Penelope Spheeris]]{{spaced ndash}}who also directed{{spaced ndash}}presents several of the ''Our Gang'' characters in an updated setting, and features re-interpretations of several of the original shorts. It was the first collaboration by Guay and Mazur, whose subsequent comedies were ''[[Liar Liar]]'' and ''[[Heartbreakers (2001 film)|Heartbreakers]]''.\n\nAnother film based on ''[[Our Gang]]'', ''[[The Little Rascals Save the Day]]'', was released as a [[direct-to-video]] feature in 2014.\n\n==Plot==\nSpanky McFarland ([[Travis Tedford]]) is the president of the \"He-Man Woman Haters Club\" with many school-aged boys from around the neighborhood as members. Alfalfa Switzer ([[Bug Hall]]), Spanky's best friend, has been chosen to be the driver for the club's prize-winning go-kart, \"The Blur\", in the upcoming [[Soap Box Derby]] go-kart race. However, Alfalfa is nowhere to be found.\n\nThe boys go to find Alfalfa and discover him in the company of his sweetheart Darla (Brittany Ashton Holmes), with whom he is forbidden to be in love because she is a girl, which goes against club rules. Alfalfa invites Darla on a picnic, and to prove his devotion to her, he agrees to have the picnic inside the clubhouse. Unbeknownst to Alfalfa, his fellow club members find out about his plans.\n\nAt the picnic, Alfalfa and Darla think they are alone, but the other club members secretly pull several silly pranks to sabotage their romantic date (whoopee cushion, cat litter in sandwiches, etc.). When they finally reveal themselves and demand to come inside the clubhouse, Alfalfa frantically tries to convince Darla to hide in the closet, which leads her to mistakenly believe that Alfalfa feels ashamed of her. In the frenzy, a candle flame gets out of control, ultimately causing the clubhouse to burn down.\n\nDarla breaks up with Alfalfa and turns her attentions towards Waldo ([[Blake McIver Ewing]]), the new kid in town whose father ([[Donald Trump]]) is an oil tycoon. Because Alfalfa burned down the clubhouse and also fraternized with a girl, he is assigned by Stymie (Kevin Jamal Woods) to guard the go-kart until the day of the race.\n\nAlfalfa makes several attempts to win back Darla, including sending her a fake love note. When that fails, Spanky goes with him to formally break things off with Darla. They are initially denied entrance to her ballet recital, but Spanky insists that they will wait for Darla to come out; Spanky gives Alfalfa a [[frog]] to play with while they wait. They are soon spotted by the neighborhood bullies, Butch (Sam Saletta) and Woim (Blake Jeremy Collins), who chase them inside the building. To escape, Spanky and Alfalfa duck into a costume room and disguise themselves as ballerinas in pink tights, tutus, and wigs. They manage to evade the bullies, but they attempt to enter another room to get out of their disguises, which are tight and uncomfortable. They are surprised to find the room filled with girls, including Darla, dressed in identical ballet outfits. The boys nervously pretend to be in the recital that is about to take place, but Alfalfa almost gives them away when the frog he is still holding croaks. Just as they are about to back out of the room, the ballet mistress ([[Lea Thompson]]) enters and ushers them all on stage.\n\nThe recital begins, and the boys are horrified when the mistress announces they are performing scenes from \"The Nutcracker.\" Alfalfa hands the frog to Spanky, but Spanky drops the frog into the waistband of Alfalfa's tights. Alfalfa squirms in discomfort as the slimy frog wriggles around in his tights, turning the show to chaos as he tries to catch it while still dancing along. The girls break out into laughter, along with the audience. The recital ends, and the boys run off stage and Alfalfa quickly ducks behind a curtain and strips out of his disguise in order to get the frog out.\n\nThe ballet mistress, furious that the boys ruined her recital, confronts them and throws them out immediately, Alfalfa in his underwear and Spanky still in drag. Butch and Woim are waiting for them outside the door, so Spanky distracts them while Alfalfa sneaks out. When Spanky loses his wig, the bullies give chase. Spanky manages to lose them, but they bump into Alfalfa, who is trying to run home in his underwear. Butch and Woim chase Alfalfa into a mansion, but are turned away by the maid. Escaping through the back door, Alfalfa is chased by Fifi, Waldo's [[Doberman]], and he leaps into a pool and swims to the other side. As he climbs out, he notices his underwear floating on the surface of the pool. As Alfalfa retrieves his underwear, he discovers Darla and Waldo in a hot tub, laughing at him, to his embarrassment. Waldo's dog then chases Alfalfa off the property.\n\nAt the carnival talent show the day before the race, the boys try to fund-raise $450, the cost of the lumber needed to rebuild their clubhouse. The youngest club members, Buckwheat ([[Ross Bagley|Ross Elliot Bagley]]) and Porky (Zachary Mabry), have unwittingly come up with $500, not realizing that their method for earning the money was not exactly honest. Their school teacher, Miss Crabtree ([[Daryl Hannah]]), finds out about the scheme and confronts Spanky, but he convinces her to donate the money to be given as first prize in the go-kart derby.\n\nAlfalfa once again tries to win Darla back, this time through song, being that Darla mentioned after she dumped him that the only thing she ever really missed about him was his singing voice. Waldo and Darla have also entered the show in a duet. Alfalfa then requests the chance to perform for her and win her back. However, Waldo sabotages his attempts to serenade her by putting soap in his drinking water, causing him to burp out bubbles all throughout his song.\n\nAs a result of Alfalfa's carelessness, \"The Blur\" is eventually stolen by Butch and Woim, so that now, in addition to having to rebuild the clubhouse, the boys need a new go-kart. They band together to build \"Blur 2: The Sequel,\" and on the day before the race, Spanky and Alfalfa (who previously had a falling out when the latter discovers the gang's \"prank list\", which was the proof that the gang sabotaged Alfalfa's picnic with Darla) reconcile their friendship and decide to ride in the two-seat go-kart together. They hope to win the prize money and the trophy, which is to be presented to the winners by A.J. Ferguson.\n\nButch and Woim make several sneaky attempts to stop Alfalfa and Spanky from winning the race. Waldo and Darla are also in the race, but they are eventually annoyed with each other, and Waldo seemingly kicks Darla out from his car. In a wild dash to the finish, and despite the many scrapes and crashes throughout the race, \"The Blur 2\" crosses the finish line ahead of the pack in a photo-finish between \"The Blur\" and \"The Blur 2\" literally by a hair, due to Alfalfa's pointy hairstyle. After the race, Butch and Woim are angry towards Alfalfa because he won the trophy and the prize money. They attempt to beat him up, but Alfalfa finally stands up for himself and punches Butch in the face, knocking him into a pool of pig slop. Woim then gets scared and jumps into the slop willingly.\n\nAlong with first prize, Alfalfa also wins back Darla, after it is revealed that it had been Darla who had kicked Waldo out of their car and finished the race alone because she found out that Waldo was responsible for the bubbles at the talent show. Meanwhile, Spanky is shocked at the trophy presentation when he finally meets his favorite driver, A.J. Ferguson, who turns out to be female ([[Reba McEntire]]). Spanky confesses to Darla that he and the boys were responsible for ruining their picnic lunch. After the club house is rebuilt, the boys collectively have a change of heart towards membership and they decide to welcome Darla as well as other girls into the club, adding a \"Women Welcome\" sign onto the front door.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Travis Tedford]] as [[George McFarland|Spanky McFarland]], the president of \"He-Man Women Hater's Club\" and Alfalfa's best friend\n* [[Bug Hall]] as [[Carl Switzer|Alfalfa Switzer]], Spanky's best friend\n* Brittany Ashton Holmes as [[Darla Hood|Darla]], Alfalfa's love interest\n* Kevin Jamal Woods as [[Matthew Beard (American actor)|Stymie]], the club's vice-president\n* Jordan Warkol (voice dubbed by [[Elizabeth Daily|E.G. Daily]]) as [[Billy Laughlin|Froggy]], a club member with a croaking voice and a love for amphibians\n* Zachary Mabry as [[Eugene Gordon Lee|Porky]], one of the younger members of the club\n* [[Ross Bagley|Ross Elliot Bagley]] as [[Billie Thomas|Buckwheat]], another one of the younger members of the club and Porky's best friend\n* Sam Saletta as [[Tommy Bond|Butch]], the neighborhood bully\n* Blake Jeremy Collins as [[Sidney Kibrick|Woim]], Butch's friend and sidekick\n* [[Blake McIver Ewing]] as [[Darwood Kaye|Waldo]], an obnoxious rich new kid who is very interested in Darla\n* [[Courtland Mead]] as [[John Collum|Uh-huh]] \u2013 club \"typographer\", always answers \"uh-huh\"\n* Juliette Brewer as [[Mary Ann Jackson|Mary Ann]]\n* Heather Karasek as [[Jean Darling|Jane]]\n* [[Raven-Symon\u00e9]] as Stymie's girlfriend at the club\n* [[Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen]] as the twin girls at Darla's sleepover\n* [[Mel Brooks]] as Mr. Welling, the bank teller\n* [[Lea Thompson]] as Miss Roberts, Darla's ballet instructor\n* [[Daryl Hannah]] as Miss Crabtree, the gang's schoolteacher\n* [[Reba McEntire]] as A.J. Ferguson, \"the best driver there is\"\n* [[Whoopi Goldberg]] as Buckwheat's mother\n* [[Donald Trump]] as Waldo's father\n* Eric Edwards as Spanky's father\n* Dan Carton as Alfalfa's father\n* [[George Wendt]] as Lumber store guy\n* Alexandra Monroe King and Zoe Oakes as Darla's friends\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Animals===\n* [[Pete the Pup|Petey]] Blue Nose Pitbull\n* Fifi, a doberman pinscher\n* Elmer, a white throated white Capuchin monkey and part of the Rascal's club.\n\n==Production==\nBill Thomas, Jr., son of the late Bill Thomas, who played the original Buckwheat, contacted the studio and was invited down to visit the set, but got the impression that the filmmakers did not want him or any of the surviving original cast members involved in any production capacity. The surviving cast members saw this as especially hurtful, in light of the fact that director Penelope Spheeris had previously made a point of including [[Buddy Ebsen]], from the original ''[[Beverly Hillbillies]]'', in her [[The Beverly Hillbillies (film)|1993 feature film adaptation]] of that series. Eugene Jackson, who played the original Pineapple from the silent ''Our Gang'' comedies, tried unsuccessfully to contact the studio to be a part of production, stated, \"It's real cold. They have no respect for the old-timers. At least they could have recognized some of the living legends surviving from the first films.\"<ref>Spiller, Nancy (August 6, 1994). [http://articles.latimes.com/1994-08-06/entertainment/ca-24243_1_director-penelope-spheeris/3|1 \"Not All 'Our Gang's' Here\"]. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> Filming took place from January 11, 1994 to April 6, 1994.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\n==Release==\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 23% based on reviews from 13 critics although it has an audience of 70%.<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|little_rascals|The Little Rascals}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] it has a score of 45 out of 100 based on reviews from 20 critics.<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web |title= The Little Rascals |url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-little-rascals |website= [[Metacritic]] }}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade \"A-\" on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= LITTLE RASCALS, THE (1994) A- |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 }}</ref>\n\nBrian Lowry of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety magazine]]'' wrote: \"Those who grew up watching The Little Rascals may well be intrigued by the idea of introducing their kids to this full-color, bigscreen version. Still, the challenge of stretching those mildly diverting shorts to feature length remains formidable, and one has to wonder whether an audience exists beyond nostalgic parents and their young children.\"<ref>{{cite web |date= 5 August 1994 |last1= Lowry |first1= Brian |title= The Little Rascals |url= https://variety.com/1994/film/reviews/the-little-rascals-1200438268/ |website= Variety }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''The Little Rascals'' earned $10 million at the North American box office during its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite news|title= A 'Clear' Triumph at Box Office : Movies: The Harrison Ford thriller seizes the No. 1 spot with estimated ticket receipts of more than $20 million. |publisher= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1994-08-08|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1994-08-08/entertainment/ca-24966_1_box-office/2|accessdate=2011-01-06|first=David J.|last=Fox}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Weekend Box Office |publisher= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1994-08-16|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1994-08-08/entertainment/ca-24966_1_box-office/2http://articles.latimes.com/1994-08-16/entertainment/ca-27567_1_weekend-box-office|accessdate=2011-01-11|first=Robert W.|last=Welkos}}</ref> The film grossed a worldwide total of $67,308,282.\n\n==Repurposed scenes and situations==\nMany of the gags and subplots in the film were borrowed from the original ''Our Gang/Little Rascals'' shorts. These include:\n* The scene in which Buckwheat and Porky are fishing and get their fishing lines tangled originates from a scene in the 1943 ''Our Gang'' short ''[[Three Smart Guys]]'' with [[Billie Thomas|Buckwheat]], [[Billy Laughlin|Froggy]], and [[Robert Blake (actor)|Mickey]].\n* The He-Man Woman Haters Club originally appeared in the 1937 ''Our Gang'' short ''[[Hearts are Thumps]]''; the club would return in the short ''[[Mail and Female]]'' the same year. The plots for both shorts were reused for the film. In addition, the scene where the gang ruins Alfalfa and Darla's lunch date, as well as the scene where bubbles come out of Alfalfa's mouth while he sings, were borrowed gags from ''Hearts are Thumps''. Alfalfa sending Buckwheat and Porky to deliver a love note to Darla was borrowed from ''Mail and Female''.\n* The \"hi-sign\" originally appeared in the 1935 Our Gang short ''[[Anniversary Trouble]], ''and the animated 1979 special, ''[[The Little Rascals Christmas Special]]''.\n* The children dressing up as fire fighters and attempting to put out a fire appeared in the ''Our Gang'' shorts ''[[Fire Fighters]]'' (1922), ''[[The Fourth Alarm]]'' (1926), and ''[[Hook and Ladder (1932 film)|Hook and Ladder]]'' (1932). The gag in which Spanky (Travis Tedford) winds up on a flying water hose was originally used with [[Allen Hoskins|Farina]] in ''The Fourth Alarm''.\n* The gag involving Spanky and Stymie disguising as adults appeared in a handful of ''Our Gang'' shorts. [[Mickey Daniels]] and [[Johnny Downs]] attempted to dress up as Santa Claus with this gag in the 1926 short ''[[Good Cheer]]''. [[Allen Hoskins|Farina]] and Pleurisy tried this routine in the 1929 short ''[[Election Day (1929 film)|Election Day]]''. [[Matthew Beard (American actor)|Stymie]] and [[Dickie Moore (actor)|Dickie Moore]] tried it in the 1933 short ''[[Fish Hooky]]'', while [[George McFarland|Spanky]] and [[Carl Switzer|Alfalfa]] tried pulling it off in both the 1935 short ''[[Teacher's Beau]]'' and the 1936 short ''[[Two Too Young]]''.\n* The scene in which Spanky and Alfalfa accidentally find themselves performing in a ballet recital was inspired by the plot of the 1937 short ''[[Rushin' Ballet]]''. The costumes that the duo wear are exact replicas of the costumes that the original [[George McFarland|Spanky]] and [[Carl Switzer|Alfalfa]] wore in ''Rushin' Ballet''. The gag in which Alfalfa gets a frog loose in his clothes was originally used in the 1937 short ''[[Framing Youth]]'', where Spanky was trying to convince him he had a frog in his throat.\n* Alfalfa singing \"The Barber of Seville\" originated in ''[[Our Gang Follies of 1938]]''.\n* The idea of the children building their own vehicle out of junk and scrap metal had been used in several ''Our Gang'' shorts, most notably the 1934 short ''[[Hi'-Neighbor!]]''. The gag in which the kids' car causes several adults to leap into the air was also borrowed from ''Hi'-Neighbor!'', and also appears in ''[[One Wild Ride]]'' (1925), ''[[Free Wheeling]]'' (1932), and ''[[Divot Diggers]]'' (1936).\n* Much of the Go-Cart race climax (including the gag in which the car belonging to Butch and Woim accidentally goes into reverse) was borrowed from the 1939 short ''[[Auto Antics]]''. Material from ''Hi'-Neighbor'' and ''[[Three Men in a Tub]]'' (1938) is also present.\n\n==Home media==\n''The Little Rascals'' was released on VHS and DVD in 1995 and 2004 respectively. It made its Blu-Ray debut in 2014.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Our Gang]]''\n* ''[[The Little Rascals (animated TV series)|The Little Rascals]]'' (animated TV series)\n* ''[[The Little Rascals Save the Day]]'' (2014 film)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0110366|The Little Rascals}}\n* {{tcmdb title|81582|The Little Rascals}}\n* {{allrovi movie|133736|The Little Rascals}}\n* {{mojo title|littlerascals|The Little Rascals}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|little_rascals|The Little Rascals}}\n\n{{Penelope Spheeris}}\n{{Our Gang}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Little Rascals, The}}\n[[Category:1994 films]]\n[[Category:1990s children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:Amblin Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Penelope Spheeris]]\n[[Category:Our Gang]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by William Ross]]\n[[Category:Films about children]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{short description|1994 family comedy by Penelope Spheeris}}\n{{more citations needed|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Little Rascals\n| image          = Little rascals ver2.jpg\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Penelope Spheeris]]\n| producer       = Bill Oakes<br />[[Michael King]]<br />[[Gerald R. Molen]]\n| writer         = Paul Guay<br />Stephen Mazur<br />Penelope Spheeris\n| story          = Paul Guay<br />Stephen Mazur<br />Penelope Spheeris<br />[[Mike Scott (musician)|Mike Scott]]<br />Robert Wolterstorff\n| based on       = {{basedon|''[[Our Gang]]''|[[Hal Roach]]}}\n| starring = {{Plain list |\n* [[Travis Tedford]]\n* Kevin Jamal Woods\n* Jordan Warkol\n* Zachary Mabry\n* [[Ross Bagley|Ross Elliot Bagley]]\n* [[Courtland Mead]]\n* Sam Saletta\n* Blake Jeremy Collins\n* [[Blake McIver Ewing]]\n* Juliette Brewer\n* Heather Karasek\n* Brittany Ashton Holmes\n* [[Bug Hall]]\n* Elmer\n* [[Pete the Pup|Petey]]}}\n| music          = [[William Ross (composer)|William Ross]]\n| cinematography = Richard Bowen (operator)\n| editing        = Ross Albert<br />[[Peter Teschner]]\n| studio         = [[Amblin Entertainment]]<br />[[KingWorld|KingWorld Filmed Entertainment]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1994|08|05}}\n| runtime        = 82 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          = $67.3 million\n| image_size     = 215px\n}}\n'''''The Little Rascals''''' is a 1994 American family comedy film produced by [[Amblin Entertainment]], and released by [[Universal Pictures]] on August 5, 1994. The film is an adaptation of [[Hal Roach]]'s ''[[Our Gang]]'', a series of [[short film]]s of the 1920s, 1930s, and 1940s (many of which were broadcast on television as ''The Little Rascals'') which centered on the adventures of a group of neighborhood [[children]]. The film, with a screenplay by Paul Guay, Stephen Mazur, and [[Penelope Spheeris]]{{spaced ndash}}who also directed{{spaced ndash}}presents several of the ''Our Gang'' characters in an updated setting, and features re-interpretations of several of the original shorts. It was the first collaboration by Guay and Mazur, whose subsequent comedies were ''[[Liar Liar]]'' and ''[[Heartbreakers (2001 film)|Heartbreakers]]''.\n\nAnother film based on ''[[Our Gang]]'', ''[[The Little Rascals Save the Day]]'', was released as a [[direct-to-video]] feature in 2014.\n\n==Plot==\nSpanky McFarland ([[Travis Tedford]]) is the president of the \"He-Man Woman Haters Club\" with many school-aged boys from around the neighborhood as members. Alfalfa Switzer ([[Bug Hall]]), Spanky's best friend, has been chosen to be the driver for the club's prize-winning go-kart, \"The Blur\", in the upcoming [[Soap Box Derby]] go-kart race. However, Alfalfa is nowhere to be found.\n\nThe boys go to find Alfalfa and discover him in the company of his sweetheart Darla (Brittany Ashton Holmes), with whom he is forbidden to be in love because she is a girl, which goes against club rules. Alfalfa invites Darla on a picnic, and to prove his devotion to her, he agrees to have the picnic inside the clubhouse. Unbeknownst to Alfalfa, his fellow club members find out about his plans.\n\nAt the picnic, Alfalfa and Darla think they are alone, but the other club members secretly pull several silly pranks to sabotage their romantic date (whoopee cushion, cat litter in sandwiches, etc.). When they finally reveal themselves and demand to come inside the clubhouse, Alfalfa frantically tries to convince Darla to hide in the closet, which leads her to mistakenly believe that Alfalfa feels ashamed of her. In the frenzy, a candle flame gets out of control, ultimately causing the clubhouse to burn down.\n\nDarla breaks up with Alfalfa and turns her attentions towards Waldo ([[Blake McIver Ewing]]), the new kid in town whose father ([[Donald Trump]]) is an oil tycoon. Because Alfalfa burned down the clubhouse and also fraternized with a girl, he is assigned by Stymie (Kevin Jamal Woods) to guard the go-kart until the day of the race.\n\nAlfalfa makes several attempts to win back Darla, including sending her a fake love note. When that fails, Spanky goes with him to formally break things off with Darla. They are initially denied entrance to her ballet recital, but Spanky insists that they will wait for Darla to come out; Spanky gives Alfalfa a [[frog]] to play with while they wait. They are soon spotted by the neighborhood bullies, Butch (Sam Saletta) and Woim (Blake Jeremy Collins), who chase them inside the building. To escape, Spanky and Alfalfa duck into a costume room and disguise themselves as ballerinas in pink tights, tutus, and wigs. They manage to evade the bullies, but they attempt to enter another room to get out of their disguises, which are tight and uncomfortable. They are surprised to find the room filled with girls, including Darla, dressed in identical ballet outfits. The boys nervously pretend to be in the recital that is about to take place, but Alfalfa almost gives them away when the frog he is still holding croaks. Just as they are about to back out of the room, the ballet mistress ([[Lea Thompson]]) enters and ushers them all on stage.\n\nThe recital begins, and the boys are horrified when the mistress announces they are performing scenes from \"The Nutcracker.\" Alfalfa hands the frog to Spanky, but Spanky drops the frog into the waistband of Alfalfa's tights. Alfalfa squirms in discomfort as the slimy frog wriggles around in his tights, turning the show to chaos as he tries to catch it while still dancing along. The girls break out into laughter, along with the audience. The recital ends, and the boys run off stage and Alfalfa quickly ducks behind a curtain and strips out of his disguise in order to get the frog out.\n\nThe ballet mistress, furious that the boys ruined her recital, confronts them and throws them out immediately, Alfalfa in his underwear and Spanky still in drag. Butch and Woim are waiting for them outside the door, so Spanky distracts them while Alfalfa sneaks out. When Spanky loses his wig, the bullies give chase. Spanky manages to lose them, but they bump into Alfalfa, who is trying to run home in his underwear. Butch and Woim chase Alfalfa into a mansion, but are turned away by the maid. Escaping through the back door, Alfalfa is chased by Fifi, Waldo's [[Doberman]], and he leaps into a pool and swims to the other side. As he climbs out, he notices his underwear floating on the surface of the pool. As Alfalfa retrieves his underwear, he discovers Darla and Waldo in a hot tub, laughing at him, to his embarrassment. Waldo's dog then chases Alfalfa off the property.\n\nAt the carnival talent show the day before the race, the boys try to fund-raise $450, the cost of the lumber needed to rebuild their clubhouse. The youngest club members, Buckwheat ([[Ross Bagley|Ross Elliot Bagley]]) and Porky (Zachary Mabry), have unwittingly come up with $500, not realizing that their method for earning the money was not exactly honest. Their school teacher, Miss Crabtree ([[Daryl Hannah]]), finds out about the scheme and confronts Spanky, but he convinces her to donate the money to be given as first prize in the go-kart derby.\n\nAlfalfa once again tries to win Darla back, this time through song, being that Darla mentioned after she dumped him that the only thing she ever really missed about him was his singing voice. Waldo and Darla have also entered the show in a duet. Alfalfa then requests the chance to perform for her and win her back. However, Waldo sabotages his attempts to serenade her by putting soap in his drinking water, causing him to burp out bubbles all throughout his song.\n\nAs a result of Alfalfa's carelessness, \"The Blur\" is eventually stolen by Butch and Woim, so that now, in addition to having to rebuild the clubhouse, the boys need a new go-kart. They band together to build \"Blur 2: The Sequel,\" and on the day before the race, Spanky and Alfalfa (who previously had a falling out when the latter discovers the gang's \"prank list\", which was the proof that the gang sabotaged Alfalfa's picnic with Darla) reconcile their friendship and decide to ride in the two-seat go-kart together. They hope to win the prize money and the trophy, which is to be presented to the winners by A.J. Ferguson.\n\nButch and Woim make several sneaky attempts to stop Alfalfa and Spanky from winning the race. Waldo and Darla are also in the race, but they are eventually annoyed with each other, and Waldo seemingly kicks Darla out from his car. In a wild dash to the finish, and despite the many scrapes and crashes throughout the race, \"The Blur 2\" crosses the finish line ahead of the pack in a photo-finish between \"The Blur\" and \"The Blur 2\" literally by a hair, due to Alfalfa's pointy hairstyle. After the race, Butch and Woim are angry towards Alfalfa because he won the trophy and the prize money. They attempt to beat him up, but Alfalfa finally stands up for himself and punches Butch in the face, knocking him into a pool of pig slop. Woim then gets scared and jumps into the slop willingly.\n\nAlong with first prize, Alfalfa also wins back Darla, after it is revealed that it had been Darla who had kicked Waldo out of their car and finished the race alone because she found out that Waldo was responsible for the bubbles at the talent show. Meanwhile, Spanky is shocked at the trophy presentation when he finally meets his favorite driver, A.J. Ferguson, who turns out to be female ([[Reba McEntire]]). Spanky confesses to Darla that he and the boys were responsible for ruining their picnic lunch. After the club house is rebuilt, the boys collectively have a change of heart towards membership and they decide to welcome Darla as well as other girls into the club, adding a \"Women Welcome\" sign onto the front door.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Travis Tedford]] as [[George McFarland|Spanky McFarland]], the president of \"He-Man Women Hater's Club\" and Alfalfa's best friend\n* [[Bug Hall]] as [[Carl Switzer|Alfalfa Switzer]], Spanky's best friend\n* Brittany Ashton Holmes as [[Darla Hood|Darla]], Alfalfa's love interest\n* Kevin Jamal Woods as [[Matthew Beard (American actor)|Stymie]], the club's vice-president\n* Jordan Warkol (voice dubbed by [[Elizabeth Daily|E.G. Daily]]) as [[Billy Laughlin|Froggy]], a club member with a croaking voice and a love for amphibians\n* Zachary Mabry as [[Eugene Gordon Lee|Porky]], one of the younger members of the club\n* [[Ross Bagley|Ross Elliot Bagley]] as [[Billie Thomas|Buckwheat]], another one of the younger members of the club and Porky's best friend\n* Sam Saletta as [[Tommy Bond|Butch]], the neighborhood bully\n* Blake Jeremy Collins as [[Sidney Kibrick|Woim]], Butch's friend and sidekick\n* [[Blake McIver Ewing]] as [[Darwood Kaye|Waldo]], an obnoxious rich new kid who is very interested in Darla\n* [[Courtland Mead]] as [[John Collum|Uh-huh]] \u2013 club \"typographer\", always answers \"uh-huh\"\n* Juliette Brewer as [[Mary Ann Jackson|Mary Ann]]\n* Heather Karasek as [[Jean Darling|Jane]]\n* [[Raven-Symon\u00e9]] as Stymie's girlfriend at the club\n* [[Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen]] as the twin girls at Darla's sleepover\n* [[Mel Brooks]] as Mr. Welling, the bank teller\n* [[Lea Thompson]] as Miss Roberts, Darla's ballet instructor\n* [[Daryl Hannah]] as Miss Crabtree, the gang's schoolteacher\n* [[Reba McEntire]] as A.J. Ferguson, \"the best driver there is\"\n* [[Whoopi Goldberg]] as Buckwheat's mother\n* [[Donald Trump]] as Waldo's father\n* Eric Edwards as Spanky's father\n* Dan Carton as Alfalfa's father\n* [[George Wendt]] as Lumber store guy\n* Alexandra Monroe King and Zoe Oakes as Darla's friends\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Animals===\n* [[Pete the Pup|Petey]] Blue Nose Pitbull\n* Fifi, a doberman pinscher\n* Elmer, a white throated white Capuchin monkey and part of the Rascal's club.\n\n==Production==\nBill Thomas, Jr., son of the late Bill Thomas, who played the original Buckwheat, contacted the studio and was invited down to visit the set, but got the impression that the filmmakers did not want him or any of the surviving original cast members involved in any production capacity. The surviving cast members saw this as especially hurtful, in light of the fact that director Penelope Spheeris had previously made a point of including [[Buddy Ebsen]], from the original ''[[Beverly Hillbillies]]'', in her [[The Beverly Hillbillies (film)|1993 feature film adaptation]] of that series. Eugene Jackson, who played the original Pineapple from the silent ''Our Gang'' comedies, tried unsuccessfully to contact the studio to be a part of production, stated, \"It's real cold. They have no respect for the old-timers. At least they could have recognized some of the living legends surviving from the first films.\"<ref>Spiller, Nancy (August 6, 1994). [http://articles.latimes.com/1994-08-06/entertainment/ca-24243_1_director-penelope-spheeris/3|1 \"Not All 'Our Gang's' Here\"]. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> Filming took place from January 11, 1994 to April 6, 1994.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\n==Release==\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 23% based on reviews from 13 critics.<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|little_rascals|The Little Rascals}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] it has a score of 45 out of 100 based on reviews from 20 critics.<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web |title= The Little Rascals |url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-little-rascals |website= [[Metacritic]] }}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade \"A-\" on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= LITTLE RASCALS, THE (1994) A- |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 }}</ref>\n\nBrian Lowry of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety magazine]]'' wrote: \"Those who grew up watching The Little Rascals may well be intrigued by the idea of introducing their kids to this full-color, bigscreen version. Still, the challenge of stretching those mildly diverting shorts to feature length remains formidable, and one has to wonder whether an audience exists beyond nostalgic parents and their young children.\"<ref>{{cite web |date= 5 August 1994 |last1= Lowry |first1= Brian |title= The Little Rascals |url= https://variety.com/1994/film/reviews/the-little-rascals-1200438268/ |website= Variety }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''The Little Rascals'' earned $10 million at the North American box office during its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite news|title= A 'Clear' Triumph at Box Office : Movies: The Harrison Ford thriller seizes the No. 1 spot with estimated ticket receipts of more than $20 million. |publisher= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1994-08-08|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1994-08-08/entertainment/ca-24966_1_box-office/2|accessdate=2011-01-06|first=David J.|last=Fox}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Weekend Box Office |publisher= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1994-08-16|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1994-08-08/entertainment/ca-24966_1_box-office/2http://articles.latimes.com/1994-08-16/entertainment/ca-27567_1_weekend-box-office|accessdate=2011-01-11|first=Robert W.|last=Welkos}}</ref> The film grossed a worldwide total of $67,308,282.\n\n==Repurposed scenes and situations==\nMany of the gags and subplots in the film were borrowed from the original ''Our Gang/Little Rascals'' shorts. These include:\n* The scene in which Buckwheat and Porky are fishing and get their fishing lines tangled originates from a scene in the 1943 ''Our Gang'' short ''[[Three Smart Guys]]'' with [[Billie Thomas|Buckwheat]], [[Billy Laughlin|Froggy]], and [[Robert Blake (actor)|Mickey]].\n* The He-Man Woman Haters Club originally appeared in the 1937 ''Our Gang'' short ''[[Hearts are Thumps]]''; the club would return in the short ''[[Mail and Female]]'' the same year. The plots for both shorts were reused for the film. In addition, the scene where the gang ruins Alfalfa and Darla's lunch date, as well as the scene where bubbles come out of Alfalfa's mouth while he sings, were borrowed gags from ''Hearts are Thumps''. Alfalfa sending Buckwheat and Porky to deliver a love note to Darla was borrowed from ''Mail and Female''.\n* The \"hi-sign\" originally appeared in the 1935 Our Gang short ''[[Anniversary Trouble]], ''and the animated 1979 special, ''[[The Little Rascals Christmas Special]]''.\n* The children dressing up as fire fighters and attempting to put out a fire appeared in the ''Our Gang'' shorts ''[[Fire Fighters]]'' (1922), ''[[The Fourth Alarm]]'' (1926), and ''[[Hook and Ladder (1932 film)|Hook and Ladder]]'' (1932). The gag in which Spanky (Travis Tedford) winds up on a flying water hose was originally used with [[Allen Hoskins|Farina]] in ''The Fourth Alarm''.\n* The gag involving Spanky and Stymie disguising as adults appeared in a handful of ''Our Gang'' shorts. [[Mickey Daniels]] and [[Johnny Downs]] attempted to dress up as Santa Claus with this gag in the 1926 short ''[[Good Cheer]]''. [[Allen Hoskins|Farina]] and Pleurisy tried this routine in the 1929 short ''[[Election Day (1929 film)|Election Day]]''. [[Matthew Beard (American actor)|Stymie]] and [[Dickie Moore (actor)|Dickie Moore]] tried it in the 1933 short ''[[Fish Hooky]]'', while [[George McFarland|Spanky]] and [[Carl Switzer|Alfalfa]] tried pulling it off in both the 1935 short ''[[Teacher's Beau]]'' and the 1936 short ''[[Two Too Young]]''.\n* The scene in which Spanky and Alfalfa accidentally find themselves performing in a ballet recital was inspired by the plot of the 1937 short ''[[Rushin' Ballet]]''. The costumes that the duo wear are exact replicas of the costumes that the original [[George McFarland|Spanky]] and [[Carl Switzer|Alfalfa]] wore in ''Rushin' Ballet''. The gag in which Alfalfa gets a frog loose in his clothes was originally used in the 1937 short ''[[Framing Youth]]'', where Spanky was trying to convince him he had a frog in his throat.\n* Alfalfa singing \"The Barber of Seville\" originated in ''[[Our Gang Follies of 1938]]''.\n* The idea of the children building their own vehicle out of junk and scrap metal had been used in several ''Our Gang'' shorts, most notably the 1934 short ''[[Hi'-Neighbor!]]''. The gag in which the kids' car causes several adults to leap into the air was also borrowed from ''Hi'-Neighbor!'', and also appears in ''[[One Wild Ride]]'' (1925), ''[[Free Wheeling]]'' (1932), and ''[[Divot Diggers]]'' (1936).\n* Much of the Go-Cart race climax (including the gag in which the car belonging to Butch and Woim accidentally goes into reverse) was borrowed from the 1939 short ''[[Auto Antics]]''. Material from ''Hi'-Neighbor'' and ''[[Three Men in a Tub]]'' (1938) is also present.\n\n==Home media==\n''The Little Rascals'' was released on VHS and DVD in 1995 and 2004 respectively. It made its Blu-Ray debut in 2014.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Our Gang]]''\n* ''[[The Little Rascals (animated TV series)|The Little Rascals]]'' (animated TV series)\n* ''[[The Little Rascals Save the Day]]'' (2014 film)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0110366|The Little Rascals}}\n* {{tcmdb title|81582|The Little Rascals}}\n* {{allrovi movie|133736|The Little Rascals}}\n* {{mojo title|littlerascals|The Little Rascals}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|little_rascals|The Little Rascals}}\n\n{{Penelope Spheeris}}\n{{Our Gang}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Little Rascals, The}}\n[[Category:1994 films]]\n[[Category:1990s children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:Amblin Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Penelope Spheeris]]\n[[Category:Our Gang]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by William Ross]]\n[[Category:Films about children]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7d:bf09:ff00:e8fd:8322:8f40:8186", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCritical response)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Little_Rascals_(film)"}
{"title_page": "The Promise (When in Rome song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Promise\n| cover      = When-In-Rome-The-Promise-315919.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[When in Rome (band)|When in Rome]]\n| album      = [[When in Rome (When in Rome album)|When in Rome]]\n| released   =\n* 1987 (UK)\n* 1988 (US)\n| format     =\n* [[Phonograph record|7-inch]]\n* [[Twelve-inch single|12-inch]]\n| recorded   = 1987\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooper |first=Duncan |url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/06/18/watch-sturgill-simpsons-heartmelting-cover-of-the-promise-that-old-new-wave-hit |title=Watch Sturgill Simpson's Heartmelting Cover of \"The Promise,\" That Old New Wave Hit |publisher=The Fader |date=2014-06-18 |accessdate=2016-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanyaland.com/2016/02/18/song-premiere-johnson-mcauley-arrive-with-a-blissful-cover-of-80s-classic-the-promise/ |title=Song Premiere: Johnson & McAuley arrive with a blissful cover of '80s classic 'The Promise' |publisher=Vanyaland |date=2016-02-18 |accessdate=2016-08-17}}</ref>\n* [[synth-pop]]\n| length     = 3:40\n| label      = [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n| writer     =\n* Clive Farrington\n* Michael Floreale\n* Andrew Mann\n| producer   =\n* Michael Brauer\n* Ben Rogan\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Heaven Knows (When in Rome song)|Heaven Knows]]\n| next_year  = 1989\n}}\n\n\"'''The Promise'''\" is a song by the British band [[When in Rome (band)|When in Rome]]. First released in 1987 on [[10 Records]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/When-In-Rome-The-Promise/master/97649 |title=When In Rome - The Promise at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date=2011-10-26 |accessdate=2016-08-17}}</ref> the song is the lead single from their [[When in Rome (When in Rome album)|self-titled debut album]]. It was written by all three band members: Clive Farrington, Andrew Mann and Michael Floreale. The song was released in the U.S. in 1988 and reached number 11 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart. It is the band's biggest commercial hit.\n\nIn 2020, Farrington+Mann, in collaboration with the [[City of Prague Philharmonic Orchestra|City of Prague Philharmonic Orchestra]] and Slovenia Symphonic Film Orchestra, released a 30th anniversary orchestral edition of their hit song \"The Promise\" on both CD and vinyl. The release contains eleven tracks, including remixes, extended mixes, and instrumentals.<ref>{{cite web |title=ADAY062 Farrington And Mann \"The Promise\" |url=http://www.augustday.net/aday062.html |website=August Day |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nWilliam Cooper of [[AllMusic]] spoke of the song in a review of the ''When in Rome'' album, writing, \"The 1988 hit \"The Promise\" was essentially a carbon copy of [[New Order (band)|New Order]]'s radio-friendly dance-rock. Dark yet catchy, boasting a throbbing dance rhythm, a singalong chorus, and a hypnotic melody, 'The Promise' certainly deserved the success.\"<ref name=\"allmusic2\">{{cite web|last=Cooper |first=William |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-in-rome-mw0000652626 |title=When in Rome - When in Rome : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-09-29}}</ref>  Cooper also highlighted \"The Promise\" as a standout on the album by labeling it an AMG Pick Track.<ref name=\"allmusic2\"/>\n\nOn 22 January 1989, a review of the album was published in the daily issue of the Junction City, Kansas newspaper ''Daily Union''. The review mentioned the song, saying, \"'The Promise', a hit in the United Kingdom, is typical. Starting with a piano that picks out the melody, the song throbs along electronically with clear harmonies of Mann and Farrington piercing through the catchy melody.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MbdEAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MbYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3207,1696850&dq=when+in+rome+virgin&hl=en |title = Daily Union - Google News Archive Search}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"The Promise\" was initially released as a 12\" record and reached the top of the [[Hot Dance Music/Club Play]] chart. After the release of the group's self-titled debut album, the song was re-released and peaked at number 11 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. However, the single was less successful in the band's native Britain, reaching number 58.\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1988\u20131989)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/11R0bwv.gif|title=Response from ARIA re: chart inquiry, received 12 September 2016|accessdate=2016-09-12|publisher=Imgur.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|103\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|UK Singles ([[The Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/The+Promise|title=The Official Charts Company - The Promise by When In Rome Search |date=6 May 2013|publisher=The Official Charts Company}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|58\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"allmusic1\">{{cite web|author=When in Rome |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/when-in-rome-mn0000247250/awards |title=When in Rome - Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-08-19}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' Dance/Club Play Songs Chart<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales Chart<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|}\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1989)\n!align=\"center\"|Position\n|-\n|United States (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite journal |date=December 23, 1989 |title=1989 The Year in Music: Top Pop Singles |page=Y-22 |journal=Billboard |volume=101 |issue=51 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1989|title=Billboard Top 100 \u2013 1989}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|83\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Sturgill Simpson}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Promise, The}}\n[[Category:1987 songs]]\n[[Category:1987 debut singles]]\n[[Category:1988 singles]]\n[[Category:When in Rome (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Holly Miranda songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Promise\n| cover      = When-In-Rome-The-Promise-315919.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[When in Rome (band)|When in Rome]]\n| album      = [[When in Rome (When in Rome album)|When in Rome]]\n| released   =\n* 1987 (UK)\n* 1988 (US)\n| format     =\n* [[Phonograph record|7-inch]]\n* [[Twelve-inch single|12-inch]]\n| recorded   = 1987\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooper |first=Duncan |url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/06/18/watch-sturgill-simpsons-heartmelting-cover-of-the-promise-that-old-new-wave-hit |title=Watch Sturgill Simpson's Heartmelting Cover of \"The Promise,\" That Old New Wave Hit |publisher=The Fader |date=2014-06-18 |accessdate=2016-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanyaland.com/2016/02/18/song-premiere-johnson-mcauley-arrive-with-a-blissful-cover-of-80s-classic-the-promise/ |title=Song Premiere: Johnson & McAuley arrive with a blissful cover of '80s classic 'The Promise' |publisher=Vanyaland |date=2016-02-18 |accessdate=2016-08-17}}</ref>\n* [[synth-pop]]\n| length     = 3:40\n| label      = [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n| writer     =\n* Clive Farrington\n* Michael Floreale\n* Andrew Mann\n| producer   =\n* Michael Brauer\n* Ben Rogan\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Heaven Knows (When in Rome song)|Heaven Knows]]\n| next_year  = 1989\n}}\n\n\"'''The Promise'''\" is a song by the British band [[When in Rome (band)|When in Rome]]. First released in 1987 on [[10 Records]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/When-In-Rome-The-Promise/master/97649 |title=When In Rome - The Promise at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date=2011-10-26 |accessdate=2016-08-17}}</ref> the song is the lead single from their [[When in Rome (When in Rome album)|self-titled debut album]]. It was written by all three band members: Clive Farrington, Andrew Mann and Michael Floreale. The song was released in the U.S. in 1988 and reached number 11 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart. It is the band's biggest commercial hit.\n\nIn 2020, Farrington+Mann, in collaboration with the [[City of Prague Philharmonic Orchestra|City of Prague Philharmonic Orchestra]] and Slovenia Symphonic Film Orchestra, released a 30th anniversary orchestral edition of their hit song \"The Promise\" on both CD and vinyl. The release contains eleven tracks including remixes, extended mixes, and instrumentals.<ref>{{cite web |title=ADAY062 Farrington And Mann \"The Promise\" |url=http://www.augustday.net/aday062.html |website=August Day |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nWilliam Cooper of [[AllMusic]] spoke of the song in a review of the ''When in Rome'' album, writing, \"The 1988 hit \"The Promise\" was essentially a carbon copy of [[New Order (band)|New Order]]'s radio-friendly dance-rock. Dark yet catchy, boasting a throbbing dance rhythm, a singalong chorus, and a hypnotic melody, 'The Promise' certainly deserved the success.\"<ref name=\"allmusic2\">{{cite web|last=Cooper |first=William |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-in-rome-mw0000652626 |title=When in Rome - When in Rome : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-09-29}}</ref>  Cooper also highlighted \"The Promise\" as a standout on the album by labeling it an AMG Pick Track.<ref name=\"allmusic2\"/>\n\nOn 22 January 1989, a review of the album was published in the daily issue of the Junction City, Kansas newspaper ''Daily Union''. The review mentioned the song, saying, \"'The Promise', a hit in the United Kingdom, is typical. Starting with a piano that picks out the melody, the song throbs along electronically with clear harmonies of Mann and Farrington piercing through the catchy melody.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MbdEAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MbYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3207,1696850&dq=when+in+rome+virgin&hl=en |title = Daily Union - Google News Archive Search}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"The Promise\" was initially released as a 12\" record and reached the top of the [[Hot Dance Music/Club Play]] chart. After the release of the group's self-titled debut album, the song was re-released and peaked at number 11 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. However, the single was less successful in the band's native Britain, reaching number 58.\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1988\u20131989)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/11R0bwv.gif|title=Response from ARIA re: chart inquiry, received 12 September 2016|accessdate=2016-09-12|publisher=Imgur.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|103\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|UK Singles ([[The Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/The+Promise|title=The Official Charts Company - The Promise by When In Rome Search |date=6 May 2013|publisher=The Official Charts Company}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|58\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"allmusic1\">{{cite web|author=When in Rome |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/when-in-rome-mn0000247250/awards |title=When in Rome - Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-08-19}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' Dance/Club Play Songs Chart<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales Chart<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|}\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1989)\n!align=\"center\"|Position\n|-\n|United States (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite journal |date=December 23, 1989 |title=1989 The Year in Music: Top Pop Singles |page=Y-22 |journal=Billboard |volume=101 |issue=51 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1989|title=Billboard Top 100 \u2013 1989}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|83\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Sturgill Simpson}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Promise, The}}\n[[Category:1987 songs]]\n[[Category:1987 debut singles]]\n[[Category:1988 singles]]\n[[Category:When in Rome (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Holly Miranda songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Bahiagrass", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Promise_(When_in_Rome_song)"}
