ecraft'' (book)]], a 2013 book about ''Minecraft'' and its creator Markus \"Notch\" Persson\n* [[Minecraft, Pacific Fleet]], U.S. Navy\n\n==See also==\n* [[Minecraft mod|''Minecraft'' mod]], a modification of the base ''Minecraft'' game\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "Widefox", "label": "safe", "comment": "f ws", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minecraft_(disambiguation)"}
{"title_page": "Saskatoon freezing deaths", "text_new": "{{short description|Series of deaths of Canadian Indigenous people allegedly at the hands of the Saskatoon Police Service}}\nThe '''Saskatoon freezing deaths''' were a series of deaths of [[Indigenous peoples in Canada|Canadian Indigenous]] people in [[Saskatoon]], [[Saskatchewan]] in the early 2000s. Their deaths were allegedly caused by members of the [[Saskatoon Police Service]] who arrested Aboriginal people (usually men for drunkenness and/or disorderly behaviour), and would drive them out of the city at night in winter only to abandon them.<!-- Hi! You're the person who wants to specifically say that these were murders by police.\nAlthough I sympathize with your intent, we can't say that. \"Murder\" is a term with a specific legal meaning - one which doesn't apply here. Similarly, when you're claiming that Person A caused Person B's death, you need to say 'alleged' unless you can cite a specific source. Sorry.--> The practice was known as taking Indigenous people for ''starlight tours'' <ref name=\"dispatch\">{{cite news|url=https://www.uregina.ca/alumni/news-aen-nfrcdaafdis.htm|title=New film renews community discussion about Aboriginal freezing deaths in Saskatoon|work=Dispatch|publisher=[[University of Regina]]|accessdate=15 February 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081102040422/https://www.uregina.ca/alumni/news-aen-nfrcdaafdis.htm|archivedate=2 November 2008}}</ref> and dates back to at least 1976.<ref name=\"Windspeaker\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Saskatoon+police+chief+admits+starlight+cruises+are+not+new.%28inquiry...-a0105369747|title=Saskatoon police chief admits starlight cruises are not new|date=July 1, 2003|work=Windspeaker|publisher=[[Aboriginal Multimedia Society of Alberta]]|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Incidents==\n\nVictims who died from [[hypothermia]] include Rodney Naistus, Lawrence Wegner, and [[Neil Stonechild]]. Naistus and Wegner died in 2000 and their bodies were discovered on the outskirts of Saskatoon. Inquests in 2001 and 2002 into their deaths determined they were due to hypothermia. The inquest jury's recommendations all related to police policies and police/Indigenous relations.<ref>[http://www.pch.gc.ca/ddp-hrd/docs/cat/2002/sk-eng.cfm Excerpts from Third Report of Canada on the Convention against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment]</ref> Neil Stonechild's body was found in 1990 in a field outside Saskatoon. A 2003 inquest was not able to determine the circumstances that led to his death.<ref name=\"CBC indepth\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/stonechild/index.html|title=Who was Neil Stonechild?|date=November 3, 2005|work=CBC News|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Vue\"/>\n\nIn January 2000, Darrell Night was dropped off on the outskirts of Saskatoon but was able to call a taxi from the nearby Queen Elizabeth Power Station and suffered no ill effects. The two officers involved, constables Dan Hatchen and Ken Munson of the Saskatoon Police Service, claimed that they had simply given Night a ride home and dropped him off at his own request, but were convicted of unlawful confinement in September 2001 and sentenced to eight months in [[prison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3540725/|title=Left for dead in a Saskatchewan winter|last=Brown|first=DeNeen L.|date=November 22, 2003|work=[[MSN]]|location=Saskatoon, Saskatchewan|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050915100829/http://msnbc.msn.com/id/3540725/|archivedate=September 15, 2005|url-status=dead|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/stonechild/timeline.html\n|title =  Neil Stonechild: Timeline\n|publisher = [[CBC News]]\n|date = November 3, 2005\n|accessdate = 2012-09-25}}</ref> The incident was the subject of the [[National Film Board of Canada]] documentary ''Two Worlds Colliding'' by Tasha Hubbard.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.nfb.ca/film/two_worlds_colliding/\n|title = Two Worlds Colliding\n|publisher = [[National Film Board of Canada]]\n|accessdate = 2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Saskatoon police initially insisted these were isolated incidents. But in 2003, police chief Russell Sabo admitted that there was a possibility that the force had been dumping First Nations people outside the city for years, after revealing that in 1976 an officer was disciplined for taking an Indigenous woman to the outskirts of the city and abandoning her there.<ref name=\"Windspeaker\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Saskatoon+police+chief+admits+starlight+cruises+are+not+new.%28inquiry...-a0105369747|title=Saskatoon police chief admits starlight cruises are not new|date=July 1, 2003|work=Windspeaker|publisher=[[Aboriginal Multimedia Society of Alberta]]|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, a young Indigenous man named Evan Maud in Winnipeg accused the police of taking him to the edge of the city at 4:00&nbsp;a.m., threatening him with a Taser, and taking his jacket.<ref>{{cite news\n|url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/threat-claims-shake-police-aboriginal-relations-1.918771\n|title = Threat claims shake police-aboriginal relations\n|work = [[CBC News]]\n|date = December 9, 2010\n|accessdate = 2010-12-12}}</ref> The police stated that the accusation was false and laid charges against Maud of criminal mischief, after evidence surfaced against him, including a video of Maud boarding a bus 15 minutes after being stopped by police, corroboration by police GPS, and testimony by witnesses that Maud was not wearing a jacket that night.<ref>{{cite news\n|url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/man-s-abuse-claims-false-winnipeg-police-1.944025\n|title = Man's abuse claims false: Winnipeg police\n|publisher = [[CBC News]]\n|date = December 18, 2010\n|location = Winnipeg\n|accessdate = 2012-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|url = http://cnews.canoe.ca/CNEWS/Canada/2010/12/18/16600911.html\n|title = Cops say man's freezing story a lie\n|last = Turenne\n|first = Paul\n|agency = [[Qu\u00e9becor M\u00e9dia|QMI Agency]]\n|work = [[Canoe.ca|CNEWS]]\n|date = December 18, 2010\n|location = Winnipeg\n|accessdate = 2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2018, Ken Thomas alleged that he was picked up by two Saskatoon Police officers and dropped off outside city limits at night in the cold. This accusation was investigated by the Public Complaints Commission, which stated that it was unfounded. In a news release, Saskatoon Police Chief Troy Cooper said it was unlikely that there was contact on the night of April 21, 2018 between the police and Mr. Thomas based on video and audio recordings taken from police cars.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man files complaint against police, says officers left him outside Saskatoon |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4165448/saskatoon-filed-complaint-police-alleged-starlight-tour/ |publisher=globalnews.ca |date=24 April 2018 |accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Man accusing Saskatoon police of conducting a \u2018starlight tour\u2019 hires lawyer experienced with the allegation |url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/man-accusing-saskatoon-police-of-conducting-a-starlight-tour-hires-lawyer-experienced-with-the-allegation-1.3916184 |publisher=saskatoon.ctvnews.ca |date=4 May 2018 |accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018Starlight Tour\u2019 allegation unfounded, investigation finds |url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/starlight-tour-allegation-unfounded-investigation-finds-1.4222925 |publisher=saskatoon.ctvnews.ca |date=18 December 2018 |accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In media ==\n===Film===\n\nThese incidents have been addressed in two films. Darrell Night's experiences were documented in [[Tasha Hubbard]]'s 2004 [[National Film Board of Canada]] documentary ''Two Worlds Colliding'', winner of the [[Canada Award]].<ref name=\"Vue\">{{cite news|url=http://www.vueweekly.com/article.php?id=1764|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130209011211/http://www.vueweekly.com/article.php?id=1764|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 9, 2013|title=Justice of the police|last=Thrall|first=Christopher|date=April 7, 2005|work=[[Vue Weekly]]|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"two worlds\">{{cite web|title=Two Worlds Colliding|url=http://www.nfb.ca/film/two_worlds_colliding/|work=Online film|publisher=[[National Film Board of Canada]]|accessdate=15 September 2011|format=requires [[Adobe Flash]]}}</ref> A fictional incident was also portrayed in the half-hour drama ''Out in the Cold'', directed by Colleen Murphy and starring [[Gordon Tootoosis]],<ref name=\"dispatch\"/> Matthew Strongeagle, and Erroll Kinistino.\n\n===Music===\nIn 2005, the Canadian punk rock band [[Propagandhi]] released the album ''[[Potemkin City Limits]]'', containing the song \"The Bringer of Greater Things\", which was \"Dedicated to Rodney Naistus, Neil Stonechild and Lawrence Wegner, murdered by members of the Saskatoon Police Department\" (album liner notes).\n\nCanadian musician [[Kris Demeanor]]'s song \"One Shoe\" was written about the Saskatoon freezing deaths, particularly Stonechild's.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n[[The Wailin' Jennys]]' song \"Starlight\" was also written about the freezing deaths.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn 2017, [[Mi'kmaq]] artist [[Cathy Elliott]] completed a five-week workshop with students from [[Sheridan College]] for her musical ''Starlight Tour''. This work was commissioned by the [[Grand Theatre (London, Ontario)|Grand Theatre]] in [[London, Ontario]]<ref name=\"CBC\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/london/canadian-arts-community-mourns-cathy-elliott-1.4359434|title=Canadian arts community mourns loss of Indigenous playwright|work=CBC News|access-date=2017-11-07|language=en}}</ref> in collaboration with Sheridan College's \"Canadian Music Theatre Project\"<ref name=\"NP\">{{Cite news|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/news-pmn/canada-news-pmn/nova-scotia-indigenous-playwright-actor-and-composer-dies-suddenly|title=Nova Scotia Indigenous playwright, actor remembered as \u2018a bright light\u2019|date=2017-10-17|work=National Post|access-date=2017-11-07|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Wikipedia article===\nBetween 2012 and 2016, the \"Starlight tours\" section of the Saskatoon Police Service's [[Wikipedia]] article was deleted several times. An internal investigation revealed that two of the edits originated from a computer within the police service. A spokesperson for the force denied that the removal of content was officially approved by the force.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/saskatoon-police-starlight-tours-wikipedia-delete-1.3512586 |title=Student claims Saskatoon police removed 'starlight tours' section from Wikipedia page |last=Zakraski |first=Dan |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=2016-03-31 |accessdate=2016-03-31}}</ref> On 31 March 2016, the Saskatoon ''[[The StarPhoenix|Star Phoenix]]'' reported that \"Saskatoon police have confirmed that someone from inside the police department deleted references to \"Starlight tours\" from the Wikipedia web page about the police force.\"<ref name=starphoenix>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | title=Someone at city police headquarters deleted 'starlight tour' references on its Wikipedia page| newspaper=Saskatoon StarPhoenix | date=31 March 2016| url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401195746/https://thestarphoenix.com/storyline/someone-at-city-police-headquarters-deleted-starlight-tour-references-on-its-wikipedia-page/}</ref> According to the report, a \"...police spokeswoman acknowledged that the section on starlight tours had been deleted using a computer within the department, but said investigators were unable to pinpoint who did it.\"<ref name=starphoenix /> The police spokeswoman stated that the force is working to \u201cmove forward with all of the positive work that has been done, and continues to be done that came out of the Stonechild inquiry.\u201d<ref name=starphoenix />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of cases of police brutality in Canada]]\n\n{{Portal|History|Canada}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* [[Thomas King (novelist)|King, Thomas]] (2017). ''The inconvenient indian. A curious account of native people in North America. The illustrated edition.'' Doubleday Canada. {{ISBN|978-0-3856-9016-4}}. pp.&nbsp;200\u2013201 (First ed. 2013, without illustr.)\n* {{cite book |last1=Razack |first1=Sherene |title=Dying from Improvement: Inquests and Inquiries into Indigenous Deaths in Custody |date=2015 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |isbn=978-1-4426-2891-5}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/news2/background/aboriginals/starlighttours.html \"In Depth: Aboriginal Canadians: Starlight Tours\"], ''CBC News''\n* [http://justice.gov.sk.ca/stonechild/finalreport/default.shtml], \"Final Report - Commission of Inquiry Into Matters Relating to the Death of Neil Stonechild\" \n* [http://www.ammsa.com/publications/windspeaker/conference-confronts-police-%E2%80%98culture-oppression%E2%80%99 \"Conference confronts police \u2018culture of oppression\u2019\"], ''Aboriginal Multi-Media Society''\n* [http://www.lawconnection.ca/content/police-oversight-backgrounder \"Police Oversight\"], ''Justice Education Society and Centre for Education, Law, & Society at {{abbr|SFU|Simon Fraser University}}''\n\n{{COI on Wikipedia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saskatoon freezing deaths}}\n[[Category:Police misconduct in Canada]]\n[[Category:Violence against Indigenous people in Canada]]\n[[Category:History of Saskatoon]]\n[[Category:Human rights in Canada]]\n[[Category:Deaths from hypothermia]]\n[[Category:Crime in Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Police brutality]]\n[[Category:Conflict-of-interest editing on Wikipedia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Series of deaths of Canadian Indigenous people allegedly at the hands of the Saskatoon Police Service}}\nThe '''Saskatoon freezing deaths''' were a series of deaths of [[Indigenous peoples in Canada|Canadian Indigenous]] people in [[Saskatoon]], [[Saskatchewan]] in the early 2000s. Their deaths were allegedly caused by members of the [[Saskatoon Police Service]] who arrested Aboriginal people (usually men for drunkenness and/or disorderly behaviour), and would drive them out of the city at night in winter only to abandon them.<!-- Hi!\n\nYou're the person who wants to specifically say that these were murders by police.\n\nAlthough I sympathize with your intent, we can't say that. \"Murder\" is a term with a specific legal meaning - one which doesn't apply here. Similarly, when you're claiming that Person A caused Person B's death, you need to say 'alleged' unless you can cite a specific source.\n\nSorry.--> The practice was known as taking Indigenous people for ''starlight tours'' <ref name=\"dispatch\">{{cite news|url=https://www.uregina.ca/alumni/news-aen-nfrcdaafdis.htm|title=New film renews community discussion about Aboriginal freezing deaths in Saskatoon|work=Dispatch|publisher=[[University of Regina]]|accessdate=15 February 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081102040422/https://www.uregina.ca/alumni/news-aen-nfrcdaafdis.htm|archivedate=2 November 2008}}</ref> and dates back to at least 1976. <ref name=\"Windspeaker\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Saskatoon+police+chief+admits+starlight+cruises+are+not+new.%28inquiry...-a0105369747|title=Saskatoon police chief admits starlight cruises are not new|date=July 1, 2003|work=Windspeaker|publisher=[[Aboriginal Multimedia Society of Alberta]]|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Incidents==\n\nVictims who died from [[hypothermia]] include Rodney Naistus, Lawrence Wegner, and [[Neil Stonechild]]. Naistus and Wegner died in 2000 and their bodies were discovered on the outskirts of Saskatoon. Inquests in 2001 and 2002 into their deaths determined they were due to hypothermia. The inquest jury's recommendations all related to police policies and police/Indigenous relations.<ref>[http://www.pch.gc.ca/ddp-hrd/docs/cat/2002/sk-eng.cfm Excerpts from Third Report of Canada on the Convention against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment]</ref> Neil Stonechild's body was found in 1990 in a field outside Saskatoon. A 2003 inquest was not able to determine the circumstances that led to his death.<ref name=\"CBC indepth\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/stonechild/index.html|title=Who was Neil Stonechild?|date=November 3, 2005|work=CBC News|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Vue\"/>\n\nIn January 2000, Darrell Night was dropped off on the outskirts of Saskatoon but was able to call a taxi from the nearby Queen Elizabeth Power Station and suffered no ill effects. The two officers involved, constables Dan Hatchen and Ken Munson of the Saskatoon Police Service, claimed that they had simply given Night a ride home and dropped him off at his own request, but were convicted of unlawful confinement in September 2001 and sentenced to eight months in [[prison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3540725/|title=Left for dead in a Saskatchewan winter|last=Brown|first=DeNeen L.|date=November 22, 2003|work=[[MSN]]|location=Saskatoon, Saskatchewan|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050915100829/http://msnbc.msn.com/id/3540725/|archivedate=September 15, 2005|url-status=dead|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/stonechild/timeline.html\n|title =  Neil Stonechild: Timeline\n|publisher = [[CBC News]]\n|date = November 3, 2005\n|accessdate = 2012-09-25}}</ref> The incident was the subject of the [[National Film Board of Canada]] documentary ''Two Worlds Colliding'' by Tasha Hubbard.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.nfb.ca/film/two_worlds_colliding/\n|title = Two Worlds Colliding\n|publisher = [[National Film Board of Canada]]\n|accessdate = 2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Saskatoon police initially insisted these were isolated incidents. But in 2003, police chief Russell Sabo admitted that there was a possibility that the force had been dumping First Nations people outside the city for years, after revealing that in 1976 an officer was disciplined for taking an Indigenous woman to the outskirts of the city and abandoning her there.<ref name=\"Windspeaker\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Saskatoon+police+chief+admits+starlight+cruises+are+not+new.%28inquiry...-a0105369747|title=Saskatoon police chief admits starlight cruises are not new|date=July 1, 2003|work=Windspeaker|publisher=[[Aboriginal Multimedia Society of Alberta]]|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, a young Indigenous man named Evan Maud in Winnipeg accused the police of taking him to the edge of the city at 4:00&nbsp;a.m., threatening him with a Taser, and taking his jacket.<ref>{{cite news\n|url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/threat-claims-shake-police-aboriginal-relations-1.918771\n|title = Threat claims shake police-aboriginal relations\n|work = [[CBC News]]\n|date = December 9, 2010\n|accessdate = 2010-12-12}}</ref> The police stated that the accusation was false and laid charges against Maud of criminal mischief, after evidence surfaced against him, including a video of Maud boarding a bus 15 minutes after being stopped by police, corroboration by police GPS, and testimony by witnesses that Maud was not wearing a jacket that night.<ref>{{cite news\n|url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/man-s-abuse-claims-false-winnipeg-police-1.944025\n|title = Man's abuse claims false: Winnipeg police\n|publisher = [[CBC News]]\n|date = December 18, 2010\n|location = Winnipeg\n|accessdate = 2012-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|url = http://cnews.canoe.ca/CNEWS/Canada/2010/12/18/16600911.html\n|title = Cops say man's freezing story a lie\n|last = Turenne\n|first = Paul\n|agency = [[Qu\u00e9becor M\u00e9dia|QMI Agency]]\n|work = [[Canoe.ca|CNEWS]]\n|date = December 18, 2010\n|location = Winnipeg\n|accessdate = 2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2018, Ken Thomas alleged that he was picked up by two Saskatoon Police officers and dropped off outside city limits at night in the cold. This accusation was investigated by the Public Complaints Commission, which stated that it was unfounded. In a news release, Saskatoon Police Chief Troy Cooper said it was unlikely that there was contact on the night of April 21, 2018 between the police and Mr. Thomas based on video and audio recordings taken from police cars.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man files complaint against police, says officers left him outside Saskatoon |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4165448/saskatoon-filed-complaint-police-alleged-starlight-tour/ |publisher=globalnews.ca |date=24 April 2018 |accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Man accusing Saskatoon police of conducting a \u2018starlight tour\u2019 hires lawyer experienced with the allegation |url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/man-accusing-saskatoon-police-of-conducting-a-starlight-tour-hires-lawyer-experienced-with-the-allegation-1.3916184 |publisher=saskatoon.ctvnews.ca |date=4 May 2018 |accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018Starlight Tour\u2019 allegation unfounded, investigation finds |url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/starlight-tour-allegation-unfounded-investigation-finds-1.4222925 |publisher=saskatoon.ctvnews.ca |date=18 December 2018 |accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In media ==\n===Film===\n\nThese incidents have been addressed in two films. Darrell Night's experiences were documented in [[Tasha Hubbard]]'s 2004 [[National Film Board of Canada]] documentary ''Two Worlds Colliding'', winner of the [[Canada Award]].<ref name=\"Vue\">{{cite news|url=http://www.vueweekly.com/article.php?id=1764|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130209011211/http://www.vueweekly.com/article.php?id=1764|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 9, 2013|title=Justice of the police|last=Thrall|first=Christopher|date=April 7, 2005|work=[[Vue Weekly]]|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"two worlds\">{{cite web|title=Two Worlds Colliding|url=http://www.nfb.ca/film/two_worlds_colliding/|work=Online film|publisher=[[National Film Board of Canada]]|accessdate=15 September 2011|format=requires [[Adobe Flash]]}}</ref> A fictional incident was also portrayed in the half-hour drama ''Out in the Cold'', directed by Colleen Murphy and starring [[Gordon Tootoosis]],<ref name=\"dispatch\"/> Matthew Strongeagle, and Erroll Kinistino.\n\n===Music===\nIn 2005, the Canadian punk rock band [[Propagandhi]] released the album ''[[Potemkin City Limits]]'', containing the song \"The Bringer of Greater Things\", which was \"Dedicated to Rodney Naistus, Neil Stonechild and Lawrence Wegner, murdered by members of the Saskatoon Police Department\" (album liner notes).\n\nCanadian musician [[Kris Demeanor]]'s song \"One Shoe\" was written about the Saskatoon freezing deaths, particularly Stonechild's.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n[[The Wailin' Jennys]]' song \"Starlight\" was also written about the freezing deaths.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn 2017, [[Mi'kmaq]] artist [[Cathy Elliott]] completed a five-week workshop with students from [[Sheridan College]] for her musical ''Starlight Tour''. This work was commissioned by the [[Grand Theatre (London, Ontario)|Grand Theatre]] in [[London, Ontario]]<ref name=\"CBC\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/london/canadian-arts-community-mourns-cathy-elliott-1.4359434|title=Canadian arts community mourns loss of Indigenous playwright|work=CBC News|access-date=2017-11-07|language=en}}</ref> in collaboration with Sheridan College's \"Canadian Music Theatre Project\"<ref name=\"NP\">{{Cite news|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/news-pmn/canada-news-pmn/nova-scotia-indigenous-playwright-actor-and-composer-dies-suddenly|title=Nova Scotia Indigenous playwright, actor remembered as \u2018a bright light\u2019|date=2017-10-17|work=National Post|access-date=2017-11-07|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Wikipedia article===\nBetween 2012 and 2016, the \"Starlight tours\" section of the Saskatoon Police Service's [[Wikipedia]] article was deleted several times. An internal investigation revealed that two of the edits originated from a computer within the police service. A spokesperson for the force denied that the removal of content was officially approved by the force.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/saskatoon-police-starlight-tours-wikipedia-delete-1.3512586 |title=Student claims Saskatoon police removed 'starlight tours' section from Wikipedia page |last=Zakraski |first=Dan |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=2016-03-31 |accessdate=2016-03-31}}</ref> On 31 March 2016, the Saskatoon ''[[The StarPhoenix|Star Phoenix]]'' reported that \"Saskatoon police have confirmed that someone from inside the police department deleted references to \"Starlight tours\" from the Wikipedia web page about the police force.\"<ref name=starphoenix>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | title=Someone at city police headquarters deleted 'starlight tour' references on its Wikipedia page| newspaper=Saskatoon StarPhoenix | date=31 March 2016| url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401195746/https://thestarphoenix.com/storyline/someone-at-city-police-headquarters-deleted-starlight-tour-references-on-its-wikipedia-page/}</ref> According to the report, a \"...police spokeswoman acknowledged that the section on starlight tours had been deleted using a computer within the department, but said investigators were unable to pinpoint who did it.\"<ref name=starphoenix /> The police spokeswoman stated that the force is working to \u201cmove forward with all of the positive work that has been done, and continues to be done that came out of the Stonechild inquiry.\u201d<ref name=starphoenix />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of cases of police brutality in Canada]]\n\n{{Portal|History|Canada}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* [[Thomas King (novelist)|King, Thomas]] (2017). ''The inconvenient indian. A curious account of native people in North America. The illustrated edition.'' Doubleday Canada. {{ISBN|978-0-3856-9016-4}}. pp.&nbsp;200\u2013201 (First ed. 2013, without illustr.)\n* {{cite book |last1=Razack |first1=Sherene |title=Dying from Improvement: Inquests and Inquiries into Indigenous Deaths in Custody |date=2015 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |isbn=978-1-4426-2891-5}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/news2/background/aboriginals/starlighttours.html \"In Depth: Aboriginal Canadians: Starlight Tours\"], ''CBC News''\n* [http://justice.gov.sk.ca/stonechild/finalreport/default.shtml], \"Final Report - Commission of Inquiry Into Matters Relating to the Death of Neil Stonechild\" \n* [http://www.ammsa.com/publications/windspeaker/conference-confronts-police-%E2%80%98culture-oppression%E2%80%99 \"Conference confronts police \u2018culture of oppression\u2019\"], ''Aboriginal Multi-Media Society''\n* [http://www.lawconnection.ca/content/police-oversight-backgrounder \"Police Oversight\"], ''Justice Education Society and Centre for Education, Law, & Society at {{abbr|SFU|Simon Fraser University}}''\n\n{{COI on Wikipedia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saskatoon freezing deaths}}\n[[Category:Police misconduct in Canada]]\n[[Category:Violence against Indigenous people in Canada]]\n[[Category:History of Saskatoon]]\n[[Category:Human rights in Canada]]\n[[Category:Deaths from hypothermia]]\n[[Category:Crime in Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Police brutality]]\n[[Category:Conflict-of-interest editing on Wikipedia]]\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed space before ref", "url_page": 